<font color="#FF0000">ATTN: VIETNAM VETS</font><br>
<tt>Sat May 24 18:05:47 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I respect the people who served in the Vietnam war.  If for nothing else, they served their country when called.  The conflict has since been proven unjustified but they went anyway.  As someone who did not serve in the war or in the military (I am now 31), I do believe that the country and the people owe the vets a debt of gratitude.<br><br>
However, many of the vets have since mastered the art of crying &quot;victimization&quot;.  They continually beat &quot;1990's America&quot; over the head with the mistakes that were made by a bunch of egotistical racists in &quot;1960's America&quot;. I see it almost everyday in my company's Human Resources Department.<br><br>
To put the Vietnam war into perspective, we really need to compare its effects to the effects of other great wars on the country.  OK,  58,000 U.S. servicepeople died in Vietnam.  Compare that to how many people died in the Civil war or WWII?  Did the Vietnam war change every American and people all over the world as did the Civil war and WWII?  I dare say NO.<br><br>
President Clinton, of whom I am not a fan, is ridiculed and chastized for not serving but I think he did the right thing.  I dare say that most of the folks who did serve were  hoping that they would come home and experience the same euphoric reception that their fathers received at the end of WWII.  They even thought that &quot;coming home&quot; would bring some glamor or fame to their dreary &quot;no-direction&quot; lives.  It did not happen and they feel &quot;cheated&quot;.<br><br>
What I would like to say to these whiners is simply, GET OVER IT and STOP USING THE WAR AS AN EXCUSE FOR YOUR INADEQUACIES!!!!!
<p><code>-- onyxman@hotmail.com  (A Real Friend of Vietnam Vets) </code><p>


